Letter Recognition | Assignment 2

Davide Pecchia

27/3/2018

Introduction

One of the earliest applications of predictive analytics was automatic recognition of letters, which is used in applications like sorting mail at post offices. In this problem, we will build a model that uses attributes of images of four letters in the Roman alphabet -A, B, P, and R ~to predict which letter a particular image corresponds to.

In this problem, we have more than two classifications that are possible for each observation. Such problems are called multi-class classification problems. (For this particular problem readers are referred to Chapter 8 of the textbook The Analytics Edge and to the paper Algorithmic Prediction of Health-Care Costs File available into the reading section of the course web site)

The file Letters.csv contains 3116 observations, each of which corresponds to a certain image of one of the four letters A, B, P and R. The images came from 20 different fonts, which were then randomly distorted to produce the final images; each such distorted image is represented as a collection of pixels, each of which is on or off. For each such distorted image, we have available certain attributes of the image in terms of these pixels, as well as which of the four letters the image is. These variables are:

  • Letter: The letter that the image corresponds to (A, B, P or R).

  • Xbox: The horizontal position of where the smallest box covering the letter shape begins.

  • Ybox: The vertical position of where the smallest box covering the letter shape begins.

  • Width: The Width of this smallest box.

  • Height: The height of this smallest box.

  • Onpix: The total number of on pixels in the character image.

  • Xbar: The mean horizontal position of all of the on pixels.

  • Ybar: The mean vertical position of all of the on pixels.

  • X2bar: The mean squared horizontal position of all of the on pixels in the image.

  • Y2bar: The mean squared vertical position of all of the on pixels in the image.

  • XYbar: The mean of the product of the horizontal and vertical position of all of the on pixels in the image.

  • X2Ybar: The mean of the product of the squared horizontal position and the vertical position of all of the on pixels.

  • XY2bar: The mean of the product of the horizontal position and the squared vertical position of all of the on pixels.

  • Xedge: The mean number of edges (the number of times an off pixel is followed by an on pixel, or the image boundary is hit) as the image is scanned from left to right, along the whole vertical length of the image.

  • XedgeYcor: The mean of the product of the number of horizontal edges at each vertical position and the vertical position.

  • Yedge: The mean number of edges as the image is scanned from top to bottom, along the whole horizontal length of the image.

  • YedgeXcor: The mean of the product of the number of vertical edges at each horizontal position and the horizontal position.

Here we are creating a new column, called IsB, that assumes the value \(Yes\) when the variable Letter corresponds to B while it assumes the value \(No\) in the others cases.

letters$IsB <- ifelse(letters$Letter == "B","Yes", "No")

  • Build a CART tree to predict whether or not a letter is a B, using the training set to build your model. Remember to not use the variable Letter as one of the independent variables in the model, as this is related to what we are trying to predict! Select reasonable parameter values for the model, and justify your parameter choices. What is the accuracy of this CART model on the test set?
FormulaCART <- IsB ~ Xbox + Ybox + Width + Height + Onpix + Xbar + Ybar + X2bar + Y2bar + XYbar + X2Ybar + XY2bar + Xedge + XedgeYcor + Yedge + YedgeXcor

To select the proper parameters to use for the tree construction, we try different values of minbucket and select the minimun one that maximises the \(Accuracy\)

var <- seq(from = 1, 30,1)
accuracy = c()
set.seed(123)
for (i in var) {
decision_tree <- rpart(formula = FormulaCART, 
                      method="class", 
                      data=training_set, 
                      control = rpart.control(minbucket = i))
letter_prediction_CART <- predict(decision_tree, 
                                  test_set, 
                                  type="class")
confusion_matrix_CART <- confusionMatrix(letter_prediction_CART, test_set$IsB)
accuracy[i] <- confusion_matrix_CART$overall[1]
}
df <-data.frame(minbucket=var)
df$Accuracy <- accuracy
ggplot(df, aes(minbucket,accuracy, color=accuracy)) +geom_point(shape = 16, size = 5, show.legend = T)+theme_minimal()+ggtitle("Accuracy for each minbucket's value") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face="bold", size=16))

Once selected the optimal minbuckets value, we look for the best value for maxdepth, which is the one that maximises the \(Accuracy\) for a given value of minbucket

accuracy <- c()
set.seed(123)
for (i in var) {
decision_tree <- rpart(formula = FormulaCART, 
                      method="class", 
                      data=training_set, 
                      control = rpart.control(minbucket = 6, maxdepth = i))
letter_prediction_CART <- predict(decision_tree, 
                                  test_set, 
                                  type="class")
confusion_matrix_CART <- confusionMatrix(letter_prediction_CART, test_set$IsB)
accuracy[i] <- confusion_matrix_CART$overall[1]
}
df <-data.frame(maxdepth=var)
df$Accuracy <- accuracy
ggplot(df, aes(maxdepth,accuracy, color=accuracy)) +geom_point(shape = 16, size = 5, show.legend = T)+theme_minimal()+ggtitle("Accuracy for each maxdepth's value") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face="bold", size=16))

It emerges that 6 is the optimal value for minbucket and 9 is the optimal value for maxdepth. So we create the decision tree controlling the growth with the values found before.

set.seed(123)
decision_tree <- rpart(formula = FormulaCART, 
                      method="class", 
                      data=training_set, 
                      control = rpart.control(minbucket=6, maxdepth = 9))

  • Now, build a random forest model to predict whether or not the letter is a B. Again, select reasonable parameter values for the model, and justify your parameter choices. What is the accuracy of the model on the test set?

For the nodesize value wee keep the same value found for the CART built before. So we have \(nodesize=6\) (same as minbucket) and we will find the optimal value of ntree by iterating the procedure.

var <- seq(from = 100, 1000, 100)
accuracy <- c()
set.seed(123)
for (i in var) {
random_forest <- randomForest(formula = FormulaCART, 
                             data = training_set, 
                             ntree= i, 
                             nodesize=6)
letter_prediction_forest <- predict(random_forest, test_set)
confusion_matrix_forest <- confusionMatrix(letter_prediction_forest, test_set$IsB)
accuracy[(i/100)] <- confusion_matrix_forest$overall[1]
}
df <-data.frame(ntree=var)
df$Accuracy <- accuracy
ggplot(df, aes(ntree,accuracy, color=accuracy)) +geom_point(shape = 16, size = 5, show.legend = T)+theme_minimal()+ggtitle("Accuracy for each ntree's value") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face="bold", size=16))

It emerges that the optimal number of trees for our model is 100. So we can proceed and let the forest grow!

set.seed(123)

Building a more general predictor

  • In a multi-class classification problem, a simple baseline model is to predict the most frequent class of all of the options for every observation. For this problem, what does the baseline method predict, and what is the baseline accuracy on the testing set? Do you think this simple baseline method is a useful benchmark for this problem? Why or why not?

  • Now build a classification tree to predict Letter, using the training set to build your model. (Remember not to use the variable IsB in the model, as this is related to what we are trying to predict!) Select reasonable parameter values and justify your parameter choices. What is the test set accuracy of your CART model? (HINT: When you are computing the test set accuracy using a classification matrix, you want to add everything on the main diagonal and divide by the total number of observations in the test set.)
NewFormulaCART <- Letter ~ Xbox + Ybox + Width + Height + Onpix + Xbar + Ybar + X2bar + Y2bar + XYbar + X2Ybar + XY2bar + Xedge + XedgeYcor + Yedge + YedgeXcor
var <- seq(from = 1, 30,1)
accuracy = c()
set.seed(123)
for (i in var) {
general_decision_tree <- rpart(formula = NewFormulaCART, 
                              method="class", 
                              data=training_set, 
                              control = rpart.control(minbucket = i))
new_letter_prediction_CART <- predict(general_decision_tree, 
                                      test_set, 
                                      type="class")
confusion_matrix_CART <- confusionMatrix(new_letter_prediction_CART, test_set$Letter)
accuracy[i] <- confusion_matrix_CART$overall[1]
}
df <-data.frame(minbucket=var)
df$Accuracy <- accuracy
ggplot(df, aes(minbucket,accuracy, color=accuracy)) +geom_point(shape = 16, size = 5, show.legend = T)+theme_minimal()+ggtitle("Accuracy for each minbucket's value") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face="bold", size=16))

accuracy <- c()
set.seed(123)
for (i in var) {
general_decision_tree <- rpart(formula = NewFormulaCART, 
                              method="class", 
                              data=training_set, 
                              control = rpart.control(minbucket = 21, maxdepth = i))
new_letter_prediction_CART <- predict(general_decision_tree, 
                                      test_set, 
                                      type="class")
confusion_matrix_CART <- confusionMatrix(new_letter_prediction_CART, test_set$Letter)
accuracy[i] <- confusion_matrix_CART$overall[1]
}
df <-data.frame(maxdepth=var)
df$Accuracy <- accuracy
ggplot(df, aes(maxdepth,accuracy, color=accuracy)) +geom_point(shape = 16, size = 5, show.legend = T)+theme_minimal()+ggtitle("Accuracy for each maxdepth's value") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face="bold", size=16))

It emerges that 21 is the optimal value for minbucket and 9 is the optimal value for maxdepth. So we create the decision tree controlling the growth with the values found before.

set.seed(123)

  • Now, build a random forest model to predict Letter, using the training data - again, do not forget to remove the IsB variable. What is the test set accuracy of your random forest model?
var <- seq(from = 100, 1000, 100)
accuracy <- c()
set.seed(123)
for (i in var) {
general_random_forest <- randomForest(formula = NewFormulaCART, 
                             data = training_set, 
                             ntree= i, 
                             nodesize=21)
new_letter_prediction_forest <- predict(general_random_forest, test_set)
confusion_matrix_forest <- confusionMatrix(new_letter_prediction_forest, test_set$Letter)
accuracy[(i/100)] <- confusion_matrix_forest$overall[1]
}
df <-data.frame(ntree=var)
df$Accuracy <- accuracy
ggplot(df, aes(ntree,accuracy, color=accuracy)) +geom_point(shape = 16, size = 5, show.legend = T)+theme_minimal()+ggtitle("Accuracy for each ntree's value") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face="bold", size=16))

It emerges that the optimal number of trees in this case for our model is 200. So we can proceed and let the forest grow!
